Architecture plan for Issues #3-#12: alex-0d18-test-8 canvas game foundation

Current foundation:
- The app is a minimal Vite + TypeScript browser project.
- `index.html` owns the full-window `#app-canvas` element.
- `src/main.ts` currently validates the canvas, configures the 2D context, handles
  device-pixel-ratio resizing, and renders a dark baseline background.
- The product name is `alex-0d18-test-8` per PRODUCT.md; do not invent or
  substitute another brand.

Module structure and file organization:
- `src/main.ts`: keep this as the browser bootstrap. It should find the canvas,
  create core services, start the game loop, and avoid owning gameplay logic.
- `src/core/GameLoop.ts`: fixed-timestep requestAnimationFrame loop with
  `update(dt)` and `render(ctx)` callbacks, FPS tracking, pause/stop lifecycle,
  and canvas clear responsibility until scenes take over.
- `src/core/Input.ts`: singleton-style keyboard state with `isDown(key)`,
  `wasPressed(key)`, per-frame edge reset, keydown/keyup listeners, and blur
  cleanup.
- `src/core/Scene.ts` and `src/core/SceneManager.ts`: scene interface
  (`enter`, `exit`, `update`, `render`) plus active-scene swap behavior.
- `src/entities/Entity.ts`: base entity shape/class with position, size,
  velocity, direction, alive flag, `update(dt)`, and `render(ctx)`.
- `src/entities/EntityManager.ts`: add/remove/iterate entities, update/render
  ordering, and dead-entity pruning.
- `src/physics/aabb.ts`: pure AABB helpers for overlap, point-in-box, and
  box-vs-box-list queries.
- `src/assets/AssetLoader.ts`: async image loading registry that resolves after
  all requested assets are ready and exposes typed lookup.
- `src/rendering/SpriteRenderer.ts`: spritesheet tile drawing helper with
  colored-rectangle fallback while art is absent.
- `src/tiles/TileTypes.ts`: `TileType` enum or string-literal union for Empty,
  Brick, Steel, Water, Grass, Ice, and Base plus shared tile constants.
- `src/tiles/TileGrid.ts`: width/height, tile size, `get(x,y)`, `set(x,y,type)`,
  bounds handling, and world-coordinate/grid-coordinate conversion.
- `src/tiles/BrickDamage.ts`: per-brick quadrant state and
  `damageQuadrant(...)` behavior; may live inside `TileGrid` if the state is
  tile-local and the API stays small.
- `src/tiles/renderTileGrid.ts`: render all tile types to canvas, including
  partial brick quadrants and render-order metadata for grass overlay.
- `src/types/`: introduce only when shared types outgrow the owning modules.
- Tests should sit next to source as `*.test.ts` or under `src/__tests__/`,
  following whatever convention Issue #3 establishes.

Shared types:
- Use a small `Vector2` type for positions, sizes, and velocities:
  `{ x: number; y: number }`.
- Use an `AABB` type with `{ x: number; y: number; width: number; height: number }`
  and keep collision helpers independent from canvas or entity classes.
- Use a `Direction` union (`'up' | 'down' | 'left' | 'right'`) for entities.
- Treat `dt` as seconds across update APIs. Fixed-step constants should be named
  in seconds to avoid mixing milliseconds and seconds.
- Keep grid coordinates integer tile indices and world coordinates pixel-based.

Issue dependencies and implementation order:
- #3 Add ESLint, Prettier, and Vitest configuration. This should happen before
  broad module work so future issues inherit consistent formatting, linting, and
  a working `npm test` script.
- #4 Build the core game loop skeleton. Depends on the Vite/canvas app shell and
  provides the runtime hook that later input, scenes, entities, and rendering use.
- #5 Implement keyboard input handler. Depends on the loop so `wasPressed` can be
  cleared once per frame.
- #6 Implement scene manager. Depends on the loop and should be wired as the
  loop's update/render target.
- #7 Implement entity base class and entity manager. Depends on the loop and
  should remain scene-agnostic so any scene can own an EntityManager.
- #8 Implement AABB collision detection. Depends on shared position/box types
  from the entity work but should stay pure and unit-tested.
- #9 Implement asset loader and sprite renderer. Depends on the Vite/browser
  setup; renderer should work with loaded images or fallback rectangles.
- #10 Define tile types and tile grid data structure. Depends on shared geometry
  conventions and should be unit-tested before rendering is added.
- #11 Implement brick wall sub-tile damage. Depends on tile grid/types and should
  extend brick state without changing non-brick tile behavior.
- #12 Render the tile grid to the canvas. Depends on tile types/grid, brick
  damage, and sprite/fallback rendering. Grass needs a render-order flag so it
  can draw above tanks/entities when gameplay entities arrive.

Key design decisions:
- Keep modules small and dependency direction one-way: core loop and input at
  the bottom, scenes compose entities/tiles/assets, rendering helpers do not
  own game state.
- Prefer pure functions for geometry and collision so they are easy to test with
  Vitest and do not require DOM setup.
- Keep canvas setup and resizing in bootstrap/core code; game modules should
  receive a ready `CanvasRenderingContext2D`.
- Use fallback colored rectangles for tile rendering until real sprites exist,
  matching Issue #9 instead of blocking on art.
- Avoid framework additions. The existing vanilla Vite + TypeScript shape is
  sufficient for the requested game foundation.
- Preserve strict TypeScript. Shared APIs should use explicit return types at
  module boundaries and avoid `any`.
- Keep tests focused on deterministic logic: input edge behavior with simulated
  events, scene transitions, entity pruning, AABB edge cases, tile coordinate
  conversion, and brick quadrant damage.
